A '''constitutional referendum''' was held in the [[Helvetic Republic]] on 25 May 1802.<ref name=DD>[http://www.sudd.ch/event.php?lang=en&id=ch011802 Helvetic Republic (Switzerland), 25 May 1802: Constitution] Direct Democracy {{de icon}}</ref> Unlike the constitution [[Helvetic Republic constitutional referendum, 1798|approved in 1798]], the new constitution, known as the Malmaison constitution, did not provide for any referendums.<ref name=DD/> Non-voters were assumed to have voted in favour of the new constitution, a measure put in place to prevent its rejection.<ref name=DD/> As a result, 72.17% of voters were deemed to be in favour.<ref name=DD/>
