'''Hext v Yeomans (1583)'''  <ref>'''Hext v Yeomans'''  Michalmas 11 Jac 4 Co15b</ref> is an early [[defamation]] case wherein the Court [[Judgment (law)|found]] that ''[[slander]] do not lie upon [[inference]]s''.<ref>David Hoffman, A Course of Legal Study: Respectfully Addressed to the Students of Law in the United States (W.S. Hein, 1817) [https://books.google.com.au/books?id=Doo8AAAAIAAJ&pg=PP10&lpg=PP10&dq=David+Hoffman,+A+Course+of+Legal+Study:+Respectfully+Addressed+to+the+Students+of+Law+in+the+United+States&source=bl&ots=AB8WrrW9mD&sig=PoZGLuWVEwQtVm_m3vkcdHiBEko&hl=en&sa=X&ved=0ahUKEwj8oZTF4oDWAhUBKpQKHT93AC8Q6AEIPjAH#v=onepage&q=Hext&f=false p161].</ref><ref>William Nelson, An Abridgment of the Common Law (R. Gosling, W. Mears, 1726) p103. </ref>  It was the origin of the ''[[mitior sensus]] doctrine'', imputing a mere intention to commit a crime was held to be nonactionable.

The defendant referred to as [[Yeoman]] was accused of saying to Hext ''I doubt not but to see thee hanged for stricking Mr Sydmans man, who was [[murder]]ed.'' The [[judge]] found that Yeoman had not actually asserted it was Hext who had done the murder, merely that he had [[assault|struck]] him.
