{{italic title}}
'''''Par in parem non habet imperium''''' ([[Latin]] for "equals have no sovereignty over each other") is a general principle of [[international law]], forming the basis of [[state immunity]].<ref>D. LIEBS, ''Lateinische Rechtsregeln und Rechtssprichwörter'', Frankfurt, C. H. Beck, 2007, 168.</ref><ref>G. DAHM and J. DELBRÜCK, ''Rüdiger Wolfrum: Völkerrecht'', Berlin, Walter de Gruyter, 1989, 277/295.</ref> Because of this principle, a sovereign state cannot excercise jurisdiction over another sovereign state.<ref>Y. DINSTEIN, "Par in parem non habet imperium", ''Isr. L. Rev.'' 1966, 407-408.</ref><ref>B. VAN SCHAACK, "Par in Parem Imperium Non Habet: Complementarity and the Crime of Aggression", ''Int'l Crim. Just.'' 2012, 149.</ref><ref>G. CORNIL, "ACQUISITION DE LA POSSESSION PAR REPRESENTANT EN DROIT ROMAIN", ''Rev. Droit Int'l & Legis. Comp.'' 1905, 127.</ref>

