{{EngvarB|date=May 2013}}
{{Use dmy dates|date=May 2013}}
The '''''Venpet''–''Venoil'' collision''' was a [[Collision|maritime accident]] involving sister [[supertanker]]s; the [[Liberia]]n-registered ''Venoil'' and ''Venpet'', in [[Fog|dense fog]] off the coast of [[South Africa]] on 16 December 1977.<ref>{{cite news|title=Venpet Venoil collision|url=https://incidentnews.noaa.gov/incident/6239|accessdate=20 April 2018|agency=NOAA Incident news|publisher=NOAA|date=16 December 1977}}</ref> The tankers were travelling in opposite directions; the ''Venoil'' fully laden with over 250,000 [[tonnes]] of [[crude oil]] bound for [[Nova Scotia]] and the ''Venpet'', travelling in [[Sailing ballast|ballast]], headed for [[Kharg Island]], Iran. The ''Venoil'' ploughed into the ''Venpet'', eventually leading to the spilling of approximately 26,600–30,500 tonnes of [[crude oil]].<ref>{{cite web|title=Ships particulars - MT Venpet and MT Venoil collision|url=http://www.aukevisser.nl/supertankers/id320.htm|website=www.aukevisser.nl|accessdate=20 April 2018}}</ref>

==History==
Both tankers were constructed in [[Nagasaki]], Japan by [[Mitsubishi Heavy Industries|Mitsubishi Heavy Industries, Ltd]], work beginning on the ''Venoil'' in October 1972 and the ''Venpet'' in January 1973.<ref name="Venoil History">{{cite news|url=http://www.aukevisser.nl/supertankers/id320.htm|title=Venoil History |accessdate=2011-05-05 |publisher=aukevisser.nl}}</ref><ref name="Venpet History">{{cite news|url=http://www.aukevisser.nl/supertankers/id323.htm|title=Venpet History |accessdate=2011-05-05 |publisher=aukevisser.nl}}</ref> The vessels were completed in March and June 1973 respectively at the cost of approximately $28m each.<ref name="DISASTERS: The Wreck of the Two Sisters">{{cite news|url=http://www.time.com/time/magazine/article/0,9171,919213,00.html|title=DISASTERS: The Wreck of the Two Sisters |accessdate=2011-05-05 |publisher=time.com|date=26 December 1977}}</ref> Each vessel was more than 330,000 [[deadweight tonnage|deadweight]] (DWT) which, at the time, classified them as [[Oil tanker#Size_categories|Very Large Crude Carriers]] (VLCCs). The current classification for vessels over 300,000 DWT is [[Oil tanker#Size_categories|Ultra Large Crude Carriers]] (ULCC).<ref name="eagle.org">{{cite journal | last=Evangelista | first=Joe, Ed. | title=Scaling the Tanker Market | journal=Surveyor | volume= | issue=4 | pages=5–11 | publisher=American Bureau of Shipping |date=Winter 2002 | url=http://www.eagle.org/NEWS/pubs/pdfs/SurveyorWinter02.pdf | accessdate=2011-05-05|format=PDF}}</ref>

