The ships met on the morning of 16 December 1977.<ref name="IncidentNews: Venoil">{{cite news |url=http://www.incidentnews.gov/incident/6239 |accessdate=2011-05-06 |title=IncidentNews: Venoil |publisher=incidentnews.gov |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110314235210/http://incidentnews.gov/incident/6239 |archive-date=14 March 2011 |dead-url=yes |df=dmy-all }}</ref> The ''Venoil'' was en route to [[Nova Scotia]] from the Iranian oil terminal at Kharg Island with between 250,000 and 307,000 tonnes of crude oil.<ref name="DISASTERS: The Wreck of the Two Sisters"/><ref name="Shippspotting">{{cite news|url=http://sandefjordskip.18.forumer.com/index.php?s=823dd1cb492b95b13e5f983ec97243cd&showtopic=2484 |accessdate=2011-05-06 |title=Shipspotting |publisher=sandefjordskip.18.forumer.com}}</ref> The ''Venpet'' was in ballast on a reciprocal course to Kharg Island from Nova Scotia, where she had already unloaded her cargo. Under dense fog, which reduced visibility to less than {{convert|370|m|ft}},<ref name="LiberianReport">{{cite news|url=http://trid.trb.org/view.aspx?id=388163 |accessdate=2011-05-06 |title=Liberian Casualty Report: Decision of the Commissioner of Maritime Affairs, R.L. and Report of the Marine Board of Investigation in the Matter of the Collision Between S/T Venoil (O.N.4414) and S/T Venpet (O.N. 4489) off the Coast of South Africa on 16 December 1977|publisher=trid.trb.org}}</ref> both ships manoeuvred in the same direction in an attempt to increase their distance from one another and avoid collision.<ref>{{cite book|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=dgK3XYYhjeIC&pg=PA49|page=49|title=A Guide to the Collision Avoidance Rules: International Regulations for Preventing Collisions at Sea|isbn=0-7506-6179-8|publisher=Butterworth-Heinemann|year=2003}}</ref> 

The bow of the ''Venoil'' collided into the side of the ''Venpet'', creating a hole {{convert|14|m|ft}} deep and {{convert|55|m|ft}} long.<ref name="DISASTERS: The Wreck of the Two Sisters"/> Both vessels caught fire, but did not explode because of their [[inert gas]] systems – the flames rising {{convert|61|m|ft}} into the air and the resulting smoke visible for up to {{convert|24|km|mi}} around. Both vessels had been travelling at around {{convert|13.5|knot|km/h}}.<ref name="c4tx.org">{{cite journal | last=Devanney | first=Jack | title=The Strange History of Tank Inerting| url=http://www.eagle.org/NEWS/pubs/pdfs/SurveyorWinter02.pdf | accessdate=2011-05-05|format=PDF}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|last1=Devanney|first1=Jack|title=The strange history of tank inerting|url=https://vdocuments.site/documents/history-of-inert-gas-in-tankers.html|website=www.vdocuments.site|publisher=The centre for tankship excellence|accessdate=20 April 2018}}</ref>

The collision occurred approximately {{convert|40|km|mi}} off the southern coast of South Africa between [[Plettenberg Bay]] and [[Cape St. Francis]].  {{Bbl to t|23980}} of [[bunker oil]] from ''Venpet's'' forward fuel tank and {{Bbl to t|170635}} of crude oil from two of ''Venoil's'' storage tanks were spilled, for a total of {{Bbl to t|194615}}, most of which was consumed by the flames; patches of emulsified oil created a {{convert|160|km|mi|adj=on}} wide slick, part of which impacted over {{convert|130|km|mi}} of the South African shoreline from [[Plettenberg Bay]] to [[Stilbaai|Still Bay]].<ref name="CTX">{{cite web|url=http://www.c4tx.org/ctx/job/cdb/precis.php5?key=19771216_001|title=CTX Casualty Database: Venpet| accessdate=2011-05-05 |publisher=c4tx.org}}</ref> Another estimate concludes the ''Venpet'' lost {{Bbl to t|31000|API=10.5}}<!--10.5 is the average of the range API 7...14 quoted in the reference--> of bunker fuel oil, and the ''Venoil'' lost {{Bbl to t|155000|API=31}} of heavy crude oil and {{Bbl to t|33000|API=10.5}} of bunker fuel oil, for a total of {{Bbl to t|219000|API=29.5}}<!--29.5 is an artificial value needed to force the template to sum the differing API values correctly -->.<ref name="CTX"/>

The majority of the crew aboard the ''Venoil'' managed to launch a lifeboat; although thirteen men who had been trapped by the flames were rescued by helicopter.<ref name="DISASTERS: The Wreck of the Two Sisters"/> Two men lost their lives in the incident.<ref name="Venoil History"/> Two British merchant ships, the [[bulk carrier]] ''Jedforest'' and the ''Clan Menzies'' rescued the remaining crews of the ''Venoil'' and ''Venpet'' respectively. The vessels were abandoned and initially drifted towards the coast as their fires eventually went out.<ref name="IncidentNews: Venoil"/> They were towed out towards the [[Agulhas Current]] to prevent them grounding on the coastline as well as ensuring that any further release of oil would be carried away from the coastline.<ref name="CTX"/>

The official investigation published in November 1985 by the Liberian marine board concluded that the collision was caused due to not maintaining a proper radar watch. Though both vessels were observing each other on the radar, they had accepted a low radar CPA of 1 mile despite the poor visibility and without taking into consideration errors of radar, especially in range and bearing.<ref>{{cite web|title=LIBERIAN CASUALTY REPORT: DECISION OF THE COMMISSIONER OF MARITIME AFFAIRS, R.L. AND REPORT OF THE MARINE BOARD OF INVESTIGATION IN THE MATTER OF THE COLLISION BETWEEN S/T VENOIL (O.N.4414) AND S/T VENPET (O.N. 4489) OFF THE COAST OF SOUTH AFRICA ON 16 DECEMBER 1977|url=https://trid.trb.org/view.aspx?id=388163|website=https://trid.trb.org/view.aspx?id=388163|publisher=Bureau of Maritime Affairs Monrovia|accessdate=20 April 2018}}</ref>

==Aftermath==
Both vessels were towed into [[Algoa Bay]] for repairs; the ''Venpet'' on 24 December and the ''Venoil'' on 1 January 1978.<ref name="CTX"/> The latter had drifted {{convert|250|mi|km}} southwest of the coast in the [[Agulhas Current]].<ref name="CTX"/> The ''Venoil'''s remaining crude oil was transferred to the tanker ''Litiopa'' before she eventually sailed to Nova Scotia.<ref name="Shippspotting"/> The damaged ships were sailed onto shipyards at [[Sasebo, Nagasaki|Sasebo]] and [[Nagasaki]] for extensive repairs.<ref name="Venoil History"/>

==Later life==
The ''Venoil'' underwent two name changes, becoming ''Resolute'' in 1981 and ''Opportunity'' in 1983. She was sailed to [[Ulsan]], [[South Korea]] for scrapping in October 1984.<ref name="Venoil History"/> Her sister ''Venpet'' was changed to ''Alexander The Great'' in 1980. In June 1984, she was hit by an [[Iraq]]i [[Exocet]] [[missile]] whilst moored at the Kharg Island oil terminal. The large scale of damage led to her scrapping, which occurred in [[Kaohsiung]], [[Taiwan]] in the October of that year.<ref name="Venpet History"/>

